               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340220-206-person1890">
                  RICHARD 
                  SPARKS
               <interp inst="t18340220-206-person1890" type="surname" value="SPARKS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-206-person1890" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-206-person1890" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am patrol of St. Dunstan's in the West. On the evening of the 10th of February, I saw the prisoner in <placeName id="t18340220-206-crimeloc1177">Fleet-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18340220-206-crimeloc1177" type="placeName" value="Fleet-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18340220-206-crimeloc1177" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340220-206-off1175 t18340220-206-crimeloc1177"></join> - I saw him take a handkerchief out of a gentleman's pocket, who was walking with his brother up Fleet-street - I took him into custody - he dropped the handkerchief - I picked it up - called the gentlemen back, and one of them said, "He has got my handkerchief" - we went to the station-house, and the gentleman gave<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183402200110"></xptr>charge of him - I produce the handkerchief which I saw him take, and afterwards drop.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. DOANE. Q. What time was it? A. A quarter before nine in the evening - I am quite sure I saw him take it - I was close, following him with my toes to his heels - I know him perfectly well before, by having followed him in the street - when I first saw him I was on the opposite side of the way, and I directly ran across and followed him - the handkerchief was not out of the pocket when I crossed over - several persons came up and said,"Let him go;" and he screamed and brought several people, and caught hold of a post - there might be other persons passing at the time.</p>
               <p>WILLIAM LEWIS. I am the brother of Benjamin Lewis- I was walking with him in Fleet-street - he is too ill to attend here - our attention was called by Sparks - my brother returned with me - he immediately saw his handkerchief in the witness's hands, and claimed it as his property - I did not lose mine - the prisoner was near enough to hear him claim it - he attended before the magistrate next morning - he lives with me, and I know he had such a handkerchief as that.(John Blankly, hair-dresser, No. 5, Ritchbell-place, Lambs-conduit-street; and 
               <persName id="t18340220-206-person1891">
                  John 
                  Jones
               <interp inst="t18340220-206-person1891" type="surname" value="Jones"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-206-person1891" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-206-person1891" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , hair-dresser, gave the prisoner a good character.)</p>
